06815nam a22009255i 9780824846367DE-B159720210830012106.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||210830t20022002hiu    fo  d z      eng d  a97808248463677 a10.1515/97808248463672doi  a(DE-B1597)483790  a(OCoLC)1076397004  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  ahiucUS-HI 4aKNC648 7aLAW0550002bisacsh04a343.5/025222100aTaking Land :bCompulsory Purchase and Regulation in Asian-Pacific Countries /ced. by David L. Callies, Tsuyoshi Kotaka. 1aHonolulu : bUniversity of Hawaii Press, c[2002] 4c©2002  a1 online resource (392 p.)  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda00tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tAcknowledgments -- tIntroduction -- tChapter 1. Planning Law and Compulsory Acquisition in Australia -- tChapter 2. Compensation System in the People’S Republic of China -- tChapter 3. Government as Ground Landlord and Land Use Regulator: The Hong Kong Experience -- tChapter 4. Japan’S Land Use Law -- tChapter 5. Land Use Planning and Compensation in Korea -- tChapter 6. Land Acquisition in Malaysia -- tChapter 7. Compulsory Land Acquisition and Compensation in New Zealand -- tChapter 8. Compulsory Purchase in Singapore -- tChapter 9. The Land Use Zoning Control and the Land Expropriation System in Taiwan -- tChapter 10. Land Planning Law System, Land Acquisition, and Compulsory Purchase Law: The Case of Thailand -- tChapter 11. The Compulsory Purchase of Private Land in the United States -- tList of Contributors -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aThe Asia-Pacific region with its rapid urbanization has generated an immediate need for both land use control and compulsory purchase by national and local governments. This book takes a comparative look at land use laws in ten Asia-Pacific countries (Australia, China, Hong Kong, Japan, Korea, Malaysia, New Zealand, Singapore, Taiwan, Thailand) as well as in the United States. A land use scholar from each country describes and analyzes compulsory land acquisition and the means through which property owners can seek compensation when government regulations or policies become so burdensome that they approach the effect of compulsory purchase. The book's major themes are land use control and eminent domain (compulsory purchase). Contributors examine land use control by focusing on land ownership, statutory framework, land use plans and planning, zoning, building regulations, courts and common law, and regulatory taking among the eleven countries. Sections on eminent domain cover the right of government to take or reclaim private property. General topics discussed include the source of authority (often a country's constitution), the public purpose and the extent of power, compensation, due process, the importance of plans, the effect of a "colonial" legal system, and the accommodation of indigenous peoples' land rights. With the publication of this volume, legal scholars and practicing land use lawyers will be able to analyze and compare for the first time the individual legal approaches of developed and developing countries in the Asia-Pacific region.Contributors: David L. Callies, Li-Fu Chen, Anton Cooray, Glenys Godlovitch, Tsuyoshi Kotaka, Murray J. Raff, William J. M. Ricquier, Eathipol Srisawaluck, Won Woo Suh, Grace Xavier, Zhen Xian Bin.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 30. Aug 2021) 0aEminent domainzAsia. 0aEminent domainzPacific Area. 0aLand usexLaw and legislationzAsia. 0aLand usexLaw and legislationzPacific Area. 7aLAW / Land Use.2bisacsh1 aBin, Zhan Xian, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aCallies, David L., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aCallies, David L., eeditor.4edt4